Date: Thu 27 Jul 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: TNA, 26 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://etna.mcot.net/query.php?nid=23619>

Thailand: Bird flu reappears; PM asks poultry producers to register
-----------------------------------------------
Following the death of a young man from bird flu and the
hospitalization of 3 other persons in Thailand's northern province of
Phichit, Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra on Wednesday [26 Jul 2006]
urged poultry farmers to register their birds with the authorities.
It appears that a new outbreak of bird flu -- the 4th of its kind --
has emerged in Thailand following the cases in Phichit, according to
public health authorities.
The reappearance of avian influenza is being taken seriously by all
government and health-related agencies.
The government has banned the movement of poultry and will notify the
World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal
Health (Office International des Epizooties or OIE).
The prime minister asked poultry producers at all levels -- whether
household farmers who keep a few birds or large-scale commercial
producers -- to inform public officials immediately if any of their
fowl died of unknown causes.
He said that a young man, a youth of 17 who died in Phichit, recently
had been infected with the H5N1 bird flu virus after having direct
contact with a dead chicken and did not notify the authorities.
The prime minister, however, said the government would not declare
the entirety of Phichit Province a bird flu outbreak area but would
declare only specific locations where the disease had been detected
as being at-risk areas.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[On 18 Jul 2006, when Thailand's Agriculture and Cooperatives
Ministry denied vehemently it had been covering up fresh outbreaks of
bird flu, the assistant to the agriculture and cooperatives minister
was quoted saying: "It's true that the disease, which is now endemic
to Thailand, may emerge again today or tomorrow" (see 20060718.1973).
Indeed a valid statement: Thailand is clearly endemically infected by
H5N1. The industrial, modern, advanced, large poultry plants seem to
have succeeded in protecting themselves by appropriate biosecurity,
avoiding vaccination; it is a different story in back-yard holdings
and in the massive fighting-cocks industry. To the objective
outsider, protecting this sector without vaccination seems extremely
difficult, if not impossible. - Mod.AS]
